{"id":635,"parent_id":0,"book_id":8,"content_id":1,"language_id":1,"display_order":635,"title":"Hospitality","subtitle":"","short_title":"Hospitality","uri":"/scriptures/bd/hospitality","content":[["div",{"id":"t1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/hospitality.t1","order":".000.1638"},[".title","Hospitality"],["div",{"id":"p1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/hospitality.p1","order":".000.1639"},"This has always been regarded by Eastern nations as a duty of the highest importance.",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/gen/18.1-5"},"Gen. 18:1–5"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/gen/19.1-3"},"19:1–3"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/ex/2.20"},"Ex. 2:20"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/judg/13.15"},"Judg. 13:15"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/judg/19.20-21"},"19:20–21"],"tell of instances of the readiness with which hospitality was offered to strangers. Such hospitality was a necessity of desert life. A host was bound at all cost to protect the life and property of his guest, even though previously unknown to him. To taste another man’s salt was to establish a claim on his protection. The New Testament enjoins the duty even more emphatically (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/matt/10.42"},"Matt. 10:42"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/matt/25.43"},"25:43"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/rom/12.13"},"Rom. 12:13"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/1-tim/3.2"},"1 Tim. 3:2"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/titus/1.8"},"Titus 1:8"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/heb/13.2"},"Heb. 13:2"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/1-pet/4.9"},"1 Pet. 4:9"],")."]]],"refs":null}
